eing irrational, is a fraught and generative affective orientation grounded in concrete histories of mistrust of government and coercive medical practices foisted on colonized peoples. By contextualizing suspicion within these longer cultural and political histories, Charles troubles traditional narratives of vaccine hesitancy while offering new entry points into discussions on racialized biopolitics, neocolonialism, care, affect, and biomedicine across the Black diaspora.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBiopoliticszBarbados. 0aCervix uterixCancerzBarbadosxPrevention. 0aFeminist theoryzBarbados. 0aHealth and racezBarbados. 0aPapillomavirus vaccinesxPolitical aspectszBarbados. 0aPapillomavirus vaccinesxSocial aspectszBarbados. 0aWomen, BlackxMedical carezBarbados. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aaffective orientation.  avaccine hesitancy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022251?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022251/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles